<!-- 03 — TECHNOLOGY -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">03 — Technology</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">True Residential Engineering — What Differentiates Service</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">True Residential's commercial lineage creates specific technical characteristics that general appliance service doesn't address correctly.</p>

    <div class="features-2col">
      <ul class="features-list">
        <li><strong>R-290 Hydrocarbon Refrigerant</strong> — Propane (R-290) has exceptional thermodynamic efficiency and near-zero environmental impact — but it's flammable, which is why it requires certified technicians for any sealed system work. Most residential appliance technicians use R-134a or R-600a tools that aren't compatible with R-290 service protocols. We hold R-290 certification and have the recovery equipment and safety procedures specifically for propane refrigerant work.</li>
        <li><strong>Stainless Steel Interior Lining</strong> — True Residential units are lined with stainless steel instead of the ABS plastic used in virtually all other residential refrigerators. This reflects the commercial heritage — restaurant refrigerators use stainless for hygiene and durability. The stainless interior has different thermal mass characteristics than plastic, which affects how we interpret temperature measurement patterns during diagnosis.</li>
        <li><strong>Commercial-Grade Compressor</strong> — True Residential uses compressors designed for continuous commercial operation — rated for 24/7 duty cycles far beyond normal residential use. These compressors are more robust than typical residential units and rarely fail prematurely when properly maintained. Most True Residential cooling failures we see are condenser, evaporator, or sensor issues — not compressor failures — reflecting the commercial-grade component quality.</li>
        <li><strong>EU-Style Auto-Close Door Hinges</strong> — True Residential uses European-style hinges with a self-closing mechanism that pulls the door shut within the last few degrees of closing. These hinges fail differently than American-style hinges: the auto-close spring loses tension gradually, leaving the door slightly ajar without the owner noticing. A door that's 2–3 degrees open allows enough air infiltration to raise internal temperature by 3–5°F over time. We check hinge tension on every True Residential temperature call.</li>
        <li><strong>Low-Vibration Design (Wine)</strong> — True Residential wine cabinets use a vibration-damping compressor mount system to prevent disturbing bottle sediment — similar to Gaggenau's approach. When the isolation mounts degrade, the compressor vibration transmits to the cabinet and bottles. We test vibration amplitude on every wine cabinet call, replacing isolation mounts before they cause compressor stress.</li>
        <li><strong>Panel-Ready Integration</strong> — True Residential offers panel-ready designs for flush cabinetry installation. The same installation clearance issues we see on GE Monogram apply here: cabinetry built too tight restricts condenser airflow. We check installation clearances before any sealed system diagnosis on all built-in True Residential units.</li>
      </ul>
      <div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#0a150f; border-color:#2a7a4a; margin-top:0">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#5abf5a">🌿 Why R-290 Certification Matters</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">A standard residential appliance technician holds EPA 608 certification for HFC refrigerants like R-134a and R-410a. R-290 (propane) is a different category — a flammable hydrocarbon refrigerant that requires specific safety protocols: proper ventilation, spark-free tools, explosion-proof recovery equipment, and knowledge of propane handling procedures. Opening a True Residential sealed system without R-290 certification isn't just technically incorrect — it's a safety issue. This is why many general appliance companies decline True Residential sealed system work. We don't decline it; we're certified for it.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#0a1015; border-color:#3a7bd5; margin-top:16px">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#6aabff">🌊 LA Outdoor True Residential</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">True Residential outdoor units in coastal LA (Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Manhattan Beach) face accelerated condenser corrosion from salt air — even with the stainless exterior. We treat every coastal outdoor True Residential call with marine anti-corrosion protocol on the condenser and electrical connections. After Santa Ana events, outdoor condenser coils need inspection — fine ash accumulates in the coil fins and restricts airflow significantly. We recommend post-Santa Ana inspection for all outdoor refrigeration in the LA market.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 — COMMON PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">04 — Common Problems</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Most Common True Residential Failures in Los Angeles</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">❄️ Temperature Running Warm</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Most common cause in LA installations: condenser coil dust accumulation. True Residential's commercial-grade compressor doesn't fail easily, but a blocked condenser forces it to work harder and lose efficiency. Annual coil cleaning prevents most temperature drift. Secondary: EU-style hinge tension loss leaving the door slightly ajar — check hinge auto-close function before any deeper diagnosis.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-common">Most Common</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🌿 Sealed System Failure (R-290)</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">When temperature drift doesn't resolve with coil cleaning, hinge adjustment, or sensor replacement, a refrigerant leak or compressor efficiency loss is the diagnosis. R-290 sealed system work requires our certified technicians — this is not a repair any general technician can legally or safely perform. We recover R-290, repair the leak, verify the evaporator, and recharge to True Residential's factory specification.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-r290">R-290 Service</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🚪 EU Auto-Close Hinge Tension Loss</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">The European-style hinge spring loses tension gradually — the door stops pulling fully closed but doesn't appear obviously open. The resulting air infiltration raises cabinet temperature by 3–5°F continuously. Most owners attribute this to a refrigeration failure. We check EU hinge auto-close tension on every True Residential temperature call. Hinge spring replacement is straightforward and OEM parts are available same-day.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-common">Most Common</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🍷 Wine Cabinet Zone Temperature Drift</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Dual-zone temperature sensor or damper fault for the affected zone — the compressor and R-290 system remain functional. Zone-specific drift is consistently a zone-level component failure, not a sealed system issue. We test each zone's sensor and damper independently before any R-290 system diagnosis. Most dual-zone wine cabinet temperature calls resolve without sealed system work.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-wine">Wine Cabinet</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🌊 Outdoor Coastal Condenser Corrosion</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Salt air deposits on outdoor condenser fins restrict airflow and accelerate metal corrosion at coastal properties. True Residential's stainless exterior handles salt exposure well, but the condenser coil fins are aluminum and vulnerable. Annual marine anti-corrosion treatment and coil cleaning at coastal properties prevents this from progressing to compressor overwork. We find this on most first-time outdoor True Residential calls at coastal properties.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-outdoor">Outdoor Units</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">💡 LED Lighting Failure</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">True Residential uses LED lighting throughout — interior, wine cabinet, and outdoor units. LED driver board failure is the most common lighting fault. The LED driver is a discrete component separate from the main control board — we test the driver independently before recommending control board replacement. Driver replacement is significantly less expensive and resolves the majority of True Residential lighting failures.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-common">Most Common</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

