<!-- 09 — FAQ -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">09 — FAQ</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">True Residential Repair FAQ</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is R-290 refrigerant and why can't most technicians service it?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">R-290 is propane — a hydrocarbon refrigerant True Residential uses for its near-zero environmental impact. Propane is flammable, which means sealed system work requires specific R-290 safety certification, explosion-proof recovery equipment, and proper ventilation protocols. Standard EPA 608 HFC certification doesn't cover R-290 work. We hold R-290 certification and are fully equipped for True Residential sealed system service.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">My True Residential refrigerator is running warm — does it need refrigerant?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Not necessarily — and checking other causes first is important. Most True Residential temperature drift in LA traces to condenser coil dust accumulation or EU-style hinge tension loss (door not sealing fully). We check both before any sealed system diagnosis. Coil cleaning and hinge service resolve a significant portion of True Residential temperature calls without R-290 work.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is True Residential the same company as True (commercial refrigeration)?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes. True Residential is the residential line from True Manufacturing, founded in 1945 in Springfield, Missouri. True Manufacturing builds commercial refrigeration equipment for restaurants, hotels, and foodservice operations worldwide. True Residential applies the same commercial engineering — stainless steel interiors, heavy-duty compressors, R-290 refrigerant — to residential undercounter and column units.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">My dual-zone True Residential wine cabinet has one zone off temperature — sealed system issue?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Almost certainly not. Zone-specific temperature drift — where one zone loses accuracy while the other holds — is consistently a zone-level sensor or damper fault, not a refrigerant or compressor issue. We test each zone's sensor and damper independently. Most dual-zone wine cabinet temperature calls resolve with a sensor replacement, without any R-290 sealed system work.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do you service True Residential outdoor refrigerators at coastal LA properties?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — and we have specific coastal protocols. Salt air accelerates condenser corrosion and ash from Santa Ana events blocks condenser airflow. We apply marine anti-corrosion treatment to condenser fins and connections on coastal outdoor True Residential calls, and recommend post-Santa Ana inspection for all outdoor refrigeration. Annual maintenance for coastal outdoor True Residential units is strongly recommended.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should True Residential appliances be serviced?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Annually for interior installations; twice per year for outdoor and coastal properties. Annual service includes condenser coil cleaning (critical in LA's dusty environment), EU hinge tension check, door gasket inspection, temperature calibration verification, drain line clearing, and R-290 system pressure check. The commercial-grade compressor will outlast most components if the condenser is kept clean and the door seals properly.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

